[[File:Mary Gluckman memorial.jpg|thumb|right|The wood contains a memorial plaque for anthropologist [[Mary Gluckman]].]]
'''Hyning Scout Wood''' is a wood between [[Yealand Conyers]] and [[Warton, Lancaster|Warton]] in [[Lancashire]].

Its features include [[limestone pavement]] and [[coppice|coppicing]] for charcoal.  The trees include [[beech]], [[larch]], [[sweet chestnut]] and [[Scots pine]].  Its woodland plants include bluebells, [[dog's mercury]], [[hart's-tongue fern]] and [[Polygonatum|Solomon's Seal]].  [[Roe deer]] and both grey and [[red squirrel]]s are found there.<ref name=WT/>  

It is managed by the [[Woodland Trust]]; is part of the [[Arnside and Silverdale]] [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]] and is recognised as a Biological Heritage Site by the county.<ref name=WT/>

