{{Orphan|date=May 2015}}

In the irrigation industry, '''matched precipitation rate (MPR)''' is a term that is used to calculate the amount of precipitation in a given area is uniform. In order to be "matched" all sprinkler heads in a given zone must have the same rate of precipitation. This can be achieved by matching the gallonage of a standard rotor to its arc and reducing range accordingly(ie. 2 gallons at 90 degrees, 4 gallons at 180 degrees, or 8 gallons if the head does a full circle) or by using MPR nozzles or sprinklers. Virtually all major sprinkler manufactures offer some type of MPR nozzle or sprinkler. The primary benefit and main goal of MPR sprinklers is to prevent water waste from run-off while still ensuring that the area receives adequate moisture.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Basics of Matched Precipitation|url=https://www.hunterindustries.com/sites/default/files/tech_irrigation_notes_basics_of_matched_precipitation.pdf|website=Hunter Industries|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Advantages of Matching Precipitation Rates|url=http://www.rainbird.com/landscape/resources/webinars/Advantages%20to%20MPR%20and%20PRS.pdf|website=RainBird|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Matching Precipitation Rates|url=http://water.ksuturf.org/index.php/how-long-to-water/matching-precipitation-rates|website=KSU Turf|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>

==Formula==
The mathematical formula for determining precipitation rate is (GPM x 96.3 ÷ area) = PR

==History==
The first MPR nozzles, the MP Rotator, were produced by [[Nelson Irrigation]] in 2003, and acquired by [[Hunter Industries]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=A WATER-SAVING SPRINKLER NOZZLE|url=http://www.ewing1.com/general/ews_prd_mprotator.htm|website=Ewing Irrigation|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hunter Industries Acquires MP Rotator Turf Sprinkle Business from Nelson Irrigation Corp|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/25267307/hunter-industries-acquires-mp-rotator-turf-sprinkle-business-from-nelson-irrigation-corporation|website=EBSCOHost|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sprinklers: Clearing the Mist|url=http://www.igin.com/print-article-2217-print.html|website=IGIN|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> Since then the popularity of these highly uniform yet low application sprinklers has caused every major sprinkler manufacturer to produce their own version of an MPR sprinkler, including [[Rain Bird]]<ref>{{cite web|title=MPR Series|url=http://www.rainbird.com/homeowner/products/sprays/MPRnozzles.htm|website=RainBird|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> and [[Toro (company)|Toro]].<ref>{{cite web|title=MPR Plus Nozzles|url=http://www.toro.com/en-us/homeowner/professional-irrigation/spray-head-nozzles/Pages/Model.aspx?pid=MPRPlusNozzles|website=Toro|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>

